external.description: Tech companies, including Google and OpenAI, have made bold claims that generative AI could significantly combat climate change by reducing global greenhouse gas emissions. However, a recent analysis by energy researcher Ketan Joshi reveals that most of these claims are not backed by solid evidence. Joshi’s report analyzed over 150 public assertions about AI’s potential to reduce climate impact and found that only a quarter of them were supported by academic research. Moreover, a third of the claims cited no evidence at all. While AI has been used in some climate solutions, like optimizing energy efficiency, tech companies' promises of AI-driven emissions reductions seem speculative and unsupported. The majority of claims conflated traditional machine learning models, which are less energy-intensive, with the large-scale generative AI systems that power tools like ChatGPT and Google Gemini, which require enormous amounts of energy. Critics argue that big tech companies are pushing a narrative that favors large AI models, which they claim will save the planet, but these models are costly to both the environment and society. As AI technologies advance, the need for transparency in their environmental impact and energy use has become more urgent.
external.title: Lack of Evidence Behind Big Tech's Claims That Generative AI Will Solve Climate Change
